41 written consent by the Commissioner of Labor as provided in Code Section 39-2-18, and
42 who is performing in a production. Such term shall also mean a person over the age of 18
43 who is currently enrolled in a public secondary school located in this state and who is
44 performing in a production.
45 (6) 'Studio teacher' means a person who is certified as a studio teacher by the Department
46 of Labor, who holds a valid five-year induction or professional certificate issued by the
47 Georgia Professional Standards Commission, or who meets the requirements of rules or
48 regulations promulgated by the State Board of Education for providing instruction and
49 related services to student performers.
50 (b) For no more than all or part of 25 school days, a student performer who is performing
51 during all or part of such allocated school days shall be credited as present by the school
52 and shall not be counted as absent, either excused or unexcused, for all or part of any day
53 missed from school due to such performance that is included on a performance certification
54 completed by the student performer's parent or guardian and the child labor coordinator or
55 studio teacher assigned to the student performer using a performance certification form
56 promulgated by the Department of Labor for this purpose. Subject to the provisions of
57 paragraph (2) of subsection (c) of this Code section, such performance certification shall
58 clearly describe the curriculum and content standards that were included in the instruction
59 and related services provided to the student performer by the studio teacher. Such
60 performance certification shall be submitted to an official of the student performer's school
61 upon such student performer's return to school after the performance which is the subject
62 of the performance certification. A single performance certification may be provided for
63 a performance that continues for consecutive school days on a single production.
64 (c)(1) Parents or guardians, studio teachers, child labor coordinators, and employing
65 units are each responsible for ensuring that the instruction and related services provided
66 to a student performer by a studio teacher are appropriate based on consideration of such
