69 (2) Whenever a student performer is engaged in a performance for three consecutive
70 school days or longer, regardless of how long the production was originally intended to
71 be, employing units and child labor coordinators shall be responsible for ensuring that the
72 instruction and related services provided to a student performer by a studio teacher
73 include appropriate curriculum and content standards that are aligned with the curriculum
74 and content standards being delivered at the student performer's school regardless of such
75 student performer's age, and the studio teacher shall be responsible for coordinating with
76 the student performer's school teachers to ensure appropriate instructional materials and
77 resources, including, but not limited to, lessons, assignments, and assessments that are
78 aligned with the school's curriculum and content standards, are being used with the
79 student performer.
80 (3) For a student performer to be credited as present as provided in subsection (b) of this
81 Code section, a parent or guardian shall provide appropriate authorization for the student
82 performer's studio teachers and school personnel to communicate regarding the student
83 performer, including, but not limited to, communications involving the student
84 performer's education records as defined in the federal Family Educational Rights and
85 Privacy Act (FERPA), 20 U.S.C. Section 1232g.
86 (d) Upon consultation with the Department of Education, the Department of Labor shall
87 promulgate a performance certification form and such policies and procedures necessary
88 to ensure compliance with this Code section."
